g.desc: The jaw is the lower part of the horses head. Strong jaw muscles help the horse chew tough grass and hay all day long.
g.title: Jaw

g.desc: The muzzle includes the nose and mouth area. Its soft and very sensitive horses often nuzzle friends or people with it!
g.title: Muzzle

g.desc: Horses breathe only through their nostrils not their mouths. Their big nostrils help them sniff out smells and get lots of air when running.
g.title: Nostrill

g.desc: The mouth is used for eating, drinking, and biting if needed. The bit (part of the bridle) sits here when riding. Horses also use their lips to explore and play.
g.title: Mouth

g.desc: Horses have large eyes on the sides of their heads. They have great vision, even in the dark, and can almost see all the way around their bodies!
g.title: Eye

g.desc: Horses can move their ears in all directions. They use them to hear, but also to show how they feel forward ears mean curious or happy, while pinned-back ears mean upset.
g.title: Ear

g.desc: This is the dip below the jaw where a bridle strap rests. Its a sensitive area that helps riders give gentle signals to the horse.
g.title: Chin groove

g.desc: The throat area includes the windpipe and muscles used for breathing and swallowing. It's also where the reins may put pressure when riding.
g.title: Throat

g.desc: The back runs from the withers to the loin. It carries the rider and helps support the saddle. A strong back is key for healthy riding.
g.title: Back

g.desc: The hoof is like a giant toenail that covers the end of the horses leg. It protects the foot and helps support the horses whole body. Hooves need trimming just like fingernails!
g.title: Hoof

g.desc: The tail helps swat away flies and also shows how a horse feels raised means excited or alert, and tucked means nervous or cold.
g.title: Tail

g.desc: The mane is the long hair on the horses neck. It helps keep flies away and can be styled for shows or left natural.
g.title: Mane

g.desc: The forelock is the tuft of hair between the ears that hangs down the forehead. It helps protect the eyes from bugs and sun.
g.title: Forelock

g.desc: Just like the hind cannon, the forecannon is the straight bone below the knee in the front leg. Its important for strength and stability.
g.title: Forecannon

g.desc: This is the straight, strong bone below the hock in the back leg. It carries much of the horses weight during motion.
g.title: Hind cannon

g.desc: The coronet is the band just above the hoof. Its where new hoof grows from a very important part for healthy feet!
g.title: Coronet

g.desc: The gaskin is the muscular part of the back leg above the hock, like a human calf. It helps power the horses movements.
g.title: Gaskin

g.desc: The hock is the large joint on the back leg, like an ankle in people. Its one of the most powerful joints and helps push the horse forward.
g.title: Hock

g.desc: The pastern is the sloped area between the hoof and the fetlock joint. It acts like a spring, helping the horse move smoothly and absorb impact.
g.title: Pastern

g.desc: The horses front knee (also called the carpus) is like a human wrist. It bends to help the horse move its leg and absorb shock when running.
g.title: Knee

g.desc: The forearm is the upper part of the front leg. It has strong muscles that help the horse lift and move its leg forward.
g.title: Forearm

g.desc: Chestnuts are small, rough patches of skin found on the inside of a horses legs. No two chestnuts are the same some people call them the horses fingerprint!
g.title: Chestnut

g.desc: The chest is the front part of the body between the front legs. It holds powerful muscles that help the horse push forward when running.
g.title: Chest

g.desc: The shoulder is the sloped bone connecting the front legs to the body. A well-angled shoulder helps the horse move with smooth, long strides.
g.title: Shoulder

g.desc: The girth is the area just behind the front legs, around the barrel. Its where a strap (also called a girth) is fastened to keep the saddle in place.
g.title: Girth

g.desc: This is a line that runs down the side of the horses neck. Inside it is the jugular vein, which vets often use to take blood or give medicine.
g.title: Jugural groove

g.desc: The neck helps a horse balance, especially when turning or moving fast. Horses use their neck to reach down and graze. A long, arched neck is often a sign of good posture.
g.title: Neck

g.desc: The crest is the top line of the horses neck, where the mane grows. Stallions (male horses) usually have a thicker crest than mares or geldings.
g.title: Crest

g.desc: The withers are the bony ridge where the neck meets the back. Its the tallest part of a horse's back and helps keep the saddle in place.
g.title: Withers

g.desc: The ribcage protects the heart and lungs. Horses have 18 pairs of ribs, and their ribcage is large so they can breathe deeply while running.
g.title: Ribcage

g.desc: The barrel is the middle part of the horses body its rib-covered belly area. This is where the lungs and stomach are, and where a saddle girth wraps around.
g.title: Barrel

g.desc: The loin is the area between the last rib and the croup. It acts like a bridge, helping connect the horses front and back ends. A strong loin helps a horse carry a rider easily.
g.title: Loin

g.desc: The croup is the top part of the horses hindquarters, just before the tail. A strong, rounded croup helps a horse with balance and power, especially when turning quickly or running fast.
g.title: Croup

g.desc: The stifle is like a horses knee, but on the back leg. Its a complex joint that helps the horse bend its leg and move smoothly. Fun fact: its similar to a human knee!
g.title: Stiffle

g.desc: The hip is the area between the horses back and the top of its hind legs. Its important for powerful movement, especially when a horse is jumping or galloping.
g.title: Hip

g.desc: The forehead is the flat area between the horses eyes and ears. It can show personality some horses have wide, expressive foreheads, and others may have a star-shaped marking here!
g.title: Forehead

g.desc: The sheath is a fold of skin that covers and protects the male horses reproductive organ. It helps keep the area clean and safe from injury. Proper care of the sheath is important for the horses health, and sometimes it needs gentle cleaning by an experienced person or a veterinarian.
g.title: Sheath
